node.text:
If you are obsessed with all things ocean-related, you’ve come to the right place. Hosted by Salt Life team member and professional surfer, Kieran Anderson, @kieranand3rson Above and Below dives into our favorite ocean-centric activities including fishing, diving, surfing, and more. Each week we will explore a different aspect of the Salt Life with an expert on the subject. Whether we are discussing the best places to catch a gnarly wave, what type of equipment to use to target and land a big fish, or diving into crystal clear beautiful waters with a speargun in hand, we assure you, you’ll be on the edge of your seat. Stay Salty!

Learn more in Introducing, Above and Below, A Salt Life Podcast: link in bio

Listen and subscribe on Spotify and Apple Podcasts!

#SaltLife #AboveAndBelowPodcast

node.text:
Huge #ThankYou for staying tuned for the entire #APPfasttrack series!! For our last #tip I would like to touch on equipment. When it comes to board sizes, for short sprints, a 12'6" has the potential to accelerate quicker than a 14'. Regardless of length, a narrower craft is likely to be faster, but it's only faster if you're stable enough to put your power down - If you're too unstable to get in a stroke with good reach and a solid catch then narrower isn't faster!! Then, no matter the length or width, having a light board will help you overcome the forces of drag faster... and the rail profile (the shape of the bottom of your board) will also matter! Whew, that was a lot - take a breath. 
Then, paddles: a large blade may help you go fast, but you need to have built up muscular strength before attempting a large blade at this intensity. So unless you have a lot of experience in the weight room and a lot of miles on the water, I would go with a smaller blade and a higher cadence. 
For Fins, they could shave off a few milliseconds, you want a smaller, lighter fin. A larger fin may help you go straighter but it's also going to increase your surface area and drag. On the other hand, if you can't paddle straight without a large fin you could lose speed trying to keep the board straight with your paddle stroke! 
And, finally, a lot of people don't take the time to clean and buff their boards regularly, but removing built-up grime can also help reduce drag and shave a few seconds off of your time! 
Bottom line, there's pros and cons to various equipment choices, and some of us just have to do the best with what we've got! That's why it is SO IMPORTANT to set your own goals and not compare yourself to others... As long as you're on the water having fun, it doesn't matter what the final times are, what really matters is staying healthy and fit.. until next time. Aloha y'all. 
@aprilzilg @404basecamp @hippostick @blackproject @onitpro

node.text:
Tip #8
This tip is GOLDEN if you put it into practice. Although you want to reach far forward when putting the blade in the water, only reach so far as you can place the ENTIRE blade in the water before you start pulling back. The start of the stroke is called the "catch" and when you do it right, you won't hear much noise or see a lot of splashing. If you hear or see water around your blade, that is a good indication to put the paddle deeper in the water next round! You may be thinking "but that makes me paddle very slow!" because when you get the whole blade in the water it feels heavy and slow. But it isn't about how fast the blade is moving, as you connect to the water and apply power the board will speed up, as it speeds up, your stroke rate will increase to match it - not the other way around. If you put the cart before the horse, so to speak, you'll just be wasting valuable energy!! GOOD LUCK and let's see those TIMES!! @appworldtour @aprilzilg

node.text: In #tip 5 we talked about facilitating lift in your paddle stroke by using your larger latissimus muscles and last week we talked about muscle tension. This week I want to bring those two tips together, and talk about activating the muscles you need in a sprint before you hit the water. This helps essentially "turn on" the proper muscles, instead of using the wrong groups of smaller muscles that are more prone to injury, and also increases muscle tension in the activated muscles. To accomplish this, I recommend using a workout band (or an old bike tire tube if all of your fitness stores are out of stock). What I'll call the "big 3" that I wouldn't do without are: Rows, Flys, and Chops. If those aren't enough for you, and if your band is long enough, you can also do a 'bear hug' pulling your hands together with the band behind your back, or put the band under your feet and do an overhead press. With those 5 moves, you'll be activated and ready to hit the water, hopefully using the proper muscle groups, to post your next #APPfastTrack time! @appworldtour @aprilzilg

node.text: In tip 3, we're back tracking a bit to talk about how to get from the required seated position to standing and sprinting! I like to sit with the handle of my board right under my center of gravity; your hands must be on the rails of the board. When you're ready to go, you're going to roll your weight forward into your hands while squeezing the rails of the board with your inner thighs. This supports your body weight while you get your toes out of the water and on to the board. Once on the board, you can use your toes to jump up into the standing/sprinting stance. The faster you can let go of the rails with your hands and get your paddle in the water - the better things will go: forward momentum will cancel out any of that wobbly side-to-side momentum (just like moving forward riding on a bicycle is easier than balancing still in a parking lot). Don't be afraid to try this at home first - if you have any sort of platform you can use that. Or you can build up by jumping into a plank position from a seated position, and then back again, for a few reps. @appworldtour

node.text:
GET STOKED 🔥 Above and Below, A Salt Life Podcast releases tomorrow!

If you are obsessed with all things ocean-related, you’ve come to the right place. Hosted by Salt Life team member and professional surfer, Kieran Anderson, @kieranand3rson Above and Below dives into our favorite ocean-centric activities including fishing, diving, surfing, and more. Each week we will explore a different aspect of the Salt Life with an expert on the subject. Whether we are discussing the best places to catch a gnarly wave, what type of equipment to use to target and land a big fish, or diving into crystal clear beautiful waters with a speargun in hand, we assure you, you’ll be on the edge of your seat. Stay Salty!

#SaltLife #AboveAndBelowPodcast

node.text:
There is a rum resurgence happening right now in the world of spirits. This liquor is being revived and reinvented by new distilleries and classic cocktail bars, and they are getting creative with their recipes. The Salt Life team is happy to celebrate the comeback of this tropical spirit by sharing this special recipe that features Zacapa Rum. This brand of rum is full of flavor and is perfect for creating delicious drinks. Have you had the chance to try Zacapa Rum? If not, this cocktail is a great way to start! #SaltLifeCocktails

Read more, and grab the recipe on today’s The Daily Salt Article. Link in bio. 

#saltlife #cocktails #thedailysalt #recipes #drinkrecipes #cocktailrecipe
